A callback is a function you give to another function, so it can call it later.
That’s it.

Think of it like this (real life)
You order food.
You tell the delivery guy:
“When you reach, call me.”
That “call me” is the callback.

You don’t call it right now.
You’re saying:

Do your job first

Then run this function later

Simple JavaScript Example:

function greet(name, callback) {
  console.log("Hello " + name);
  callback();
}


function sayBye() {
  console.log("Bye!");
}

greet("Sagar", sayBye);

Output:
Hello Sagar
Bye!


Why do callbacks exist?

Because JavaScript does a lot of stuff that takes time:

fetching data from internet

reading files

waiting for user click

timers

So you can’t always run code instantly.

Example: setTimeout
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("This runs after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);


That arrow function is a callback.

You’re telling JS:

“Wait 2 seconds, then call this.”

Example: Button click
button.addEventListener("click", () => {
  console.log("Button clicked!");
});


That function runs only when the user clicks.

Callback again.
Brutally Honest Summary
Callbacks are not special.
A callback is just:
a function passed as an argument
to be executed later
usually after something finishes
